To build a world-class AI Online Tutor that actually gets people to stop scrolling and start paying, you need to go beyond a basic chat interface. You are building a Cognitive Partnership.
Here are all the features that need to be in your "Big Important Thing" to make it a complete ecosystem.
1. The "Context Engine" (Document Upload & Processing)
 * Multi-Format Support: Users should be able to upload PDF, Word, PowerPoint, and JPG/PNG (photos of their textbooks or handwritten notes).
 * Smart Parsing: The AI doesn't just read words; it identifies Diagrams, Tables, and Formulas.
 * Knowledge Mapping: Upon upload, the AI creates a "Mind Map" of the document to show the student exactly how concepts are linked.
2. The "Lesson Architect" (Customized Session)
 * Duration Slider: 10 mins (Quick Review), 30 mins (Standard Lesson), or 60 mins (Deep Dive).
 * Goal Selection: The user chooses their "vibe":
   * Exam Prep: Focus on predicted exam questions.
   * Conceptual Understanding: Focus on analogies and "why" it works.
   * Quick Recap: Bullet points and summaries.
 * Language Bridge: The option to have the textbook in English but the explanation in a local language (isiZulu, Afrikaans, etc.).
3. The "AI Tutor" (Active Learning Interface)
 * Socratic Dialogue: The AI is programmed to never give the answer first. It provides hints, asks "What do you think?", and guides the student to the "Aha!" moment.
 * Multimodal Explanation: If a student is stuck, the AI can say: "I see you're struggling with this math formula. Here is a simplified version [LaTeX] or a real-world analogy about building a house."
 * Voice Interactivity: A "Hands-Free" mode where the student can talk to the AI while they are busy, and the AI speaks back using a natural, human-like voice.
4. The "Adaptive Assessment" (Practice Questions)
 * Dynamic Difficulty: If the student gets 2 questions right, the 3rd one gets significantly harder.
 * Active Recall Feedback: If a student answers a quiz question wrong, the AI doesn't just say "X is wrong." It explains why their specific logic was flawed based on the uploaded document.
 * Exam Style Simulation: The ability to generate questions that look like Multiple Choice, Short Answer, or Case Studies specifically tailored to a University level.
5. The "Student Analytics" Dashboard
 * Mastery Score: A 0‚Äì100% score for each uploaded document. A student knows they are "Ready for the Exam" when the score hits 90%.
 * Struggle Spots: A list of specific topics the student keeps getting wrong.
 * Study Streaks: Gamification (like Duolingo) to keep the student coming back every day.
üèó The "Smarter" Architecture (How it works behind the scenes)
| Feature | Technical Requirement | Why it's a "Global" Need |
|---|---|---|
| Document Memory | Vector Database (Pinecone/Milvus) | Allows the AI to remember a 500-page book without getting confused. |
| Personalized Pace | Adaptive Algorithms | Prevents "Cognitive Overload" (the student getting overwhelmed). |
| Instant Quiz | Generative AI (Gemini/GPT) | Traditional test banks are static; AI tests are infinite and fresh. |
üí° The "Killer" Feature: The "At-Risk" Alert
If you want to sell this to Varsity College or UJ, add a "Frustration Detector." If the AI senses the student is getting angry or giving up (based on their chat sentiment), it triggers a notification: "Hey, you've been working hard. Take a 5-minute break, or would you like me to explain this using a completely different example?"
This is the complete list. You don't need to build it all on Day 1, but this is the roadmap.
